6.
    a.
        The loudspeaker produces sound by inducing oscillating vibrations in the paper cone, which transmits that vibration into the air as sound-waves. It induces the aforementioned oscillations by alternating the direction of current in the coil. If the current is s.t. it is going into the page in the top half and going out in the bottom half, the coil will experience a force towards and move towards the left; if the current is the opposite direction, it will move towards the right. These movements are transferred to the tube and then to the paper cone, which creates sound. The device which controls the loudspeaker can alternate the amount of current and the frequency at which it changes direction to control the volume and pitch respectively of the sound produced.
