8.
    a.
        i.
            The hailstone, kept cold so that it does not melt, should be weighed on a balance, taking care that the balance has been zeroed before placing the hailstone on it and taking care that all legs are on a flat, sturdy surface. Then, measuring tape can be used to measure the circumference of the largest circle that can be drawn on the surface of the hailstone, which can be divided by pi to get its diameter; this can be confirmed by e.g. placing the hailstone between two blocks of wood or another suitably large, flat surface and measuring the distance between the two internal surfaces, which should also be the diameter. Taking the diameter, divide by two to get the radius. Convert this into centimeters, then apply the formula volume = (4/3) * (pi) * (r^3); then, convert the weight of the hailstone into grams, which is also its mass since we measured it, presumably, on Earth. The formula density (in grams per cubic centimeter) = mass (in grams) / volume (in cubic centimeters) can be applied with the aforementioned values to obtain its density. This process can be repeated with multiple hailstones and the average taken to find the average density of a generic hailstone if so desired.
        ii.
            0.94/1.1 = 0.854545454545 ~= 0.855 g/(cm^3)
    b.
        Convection is the movement of air as hot air rises and cold air sinks. This happens continuously, as as the cold air sinks, it gets heated up by the warm ground and rises up again. The hailstones would experience an imbalanced and upwards force as hot air rises as they have non-negligible cross-sectional area and hence experience drag when they have nonzero relative velocity to the surrounding air. Hence, the hailstones are lifted to the top of the cloud.
9.
    a.
        Air molecules move in random directions and have momentum. When they collide with the inner walls (which have an area), they exert a force on them, since they must change direction (change in momentum, which requires a force) otherwise they would phase through the walls, which is generally impossible. Since pressure is force/area, there must also be a pressure exerted.
    b.
        The number of air molecules in the container decreases. This is because heating increases the pressure in the container; also, heating increases the average temperature of the molecules as temperature in kelvin is proportional to average kinetic energy. All this means that particles are more likely to leave the container via the hole since they are faster and have more energy, so over time, the number of air molecules in the container must decrease.
    c.
        Because as the container cools, the average kinetic energy and so momentum and hence force per individual collision exerted on the internal walls decreases. This means less pressure is exerted on the internal walls. Normally, air would rush in from outside to equalize the pressure, but this is now not possible. Hence, since the pressure inside the container is lower than outside and since the force on the walls is lesser in magnitude than the forces acting on the container from outside (atmospheric pressure, which exerts a force in much the same manner; i.e. air molecules colliding with the walls), the container experiences a stronger force inwards than outwards, so collapses until the reduction in volume causes pressure to equalize enough for the strength of the walls to resist further collapse.
