    a.
        i.
            Because the direction of current and hence voltage induced depends on the direction of motion; as the trolley moves from left to right, current is induced up to down, and as the trolley moves from right to left current is induced down to up. Hence, as the trolley moves from left to right, the sign of the voltmeter is one way; as the trolley moves from right to left, it is the opposite sign.
        ii.
            Because it is not possible for the trolley to maintain a constant speed, as it must accelerate and decelerate at least near the ends of its path. Higher speed leads to a higher magnitude of induced voltage, so if the trolley does not pass through the magnetic field at a constant speed every time it passes through, the magnitude will change.
