    b.
        i.
            Transverse waves have oscillations and vibrations perpendicular to the axis of travel whereas longitudinal waves have oscillations etc parallel to the axis of travel.
        ii.
            Because as the boat travels towards the observer, the waves generated towards the observer are compressed as the boat is moving. The speed of those waves in water remains constant, but since the distance between waves is reduced, the wavelength decreases, and so since speed = frequency * wavelength, since speed is constant, if wavelength decreases, frequency must increase. This is also known as the doppler effect.
12.
    a.
        sqrt(2 * 10 * 1300) = 161.245154966 ~= 161.2 m/s
    b.
        i.
            When the parachute opens, the cross-sectional area of the parachutist greatly increases. The force of drag is proportional to area, so when this increase happens, the force of drag opposing the parachutist's motion increases as well. This causes an imbalanced upwards force, which causes an acceleration upwards as an imbalanced force must cause acceleration, which causes the parachutist to slow down.
        ii.
            This is because as the parachute opens, air molecules impact the parachute, and energy is transferred from the parachutist's KE store to the air's KE store. So, although the parachutist loses energy, energy is still conserved as it is simply transferred. In addition, the parachutist's GPE store must decrease since GPE = height * mass * g, and height decreases while mass and g are kept constant, so GPE must decrease; the parachutist's KE store must decrease since KE = 1/2 * mass * velocity^2, and the parachutist slows down as given, so their velocity must decrease, and mass is kept constant, so KE must decrease too.
        